Full and wide outside off, Rohit wanted to leave it alone but was a bit late in doing so. The ball takes the toe end and goes towards the slip cordon.
Good length and around off, kept out.
Wide outside off, left alone.
Skipper, Virat Kohli walks out to a huge roar from the crowd.

DRINKS! It has been a sedentary start from India to the day. The pair of Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara were happy to go about at their pace. England will be happy with that wicket. They have kept things tight and got the wicket of Pujara but they need to continue the good work and try and get at least one more before the end of this session.

Time for the DRS! Pujara has been given out LBW but he quickly goes for the review. Here comes the replays. Pad first says the umpire. Ball Tracker shows three reds. Keep walking Pujara. And he takes the review along with him.

OUT! LBW! Three reds shows the Ball Tracker and Pujara has to go. Big, big success for Leach and England. A poor, poor review from Pujara to be honest. He called for it quickly after the umpire raised the finger and did not even discuss with his batting partner. But to his dismay, it is pad first and the ball is crashing into the stumps. This is 4th time Leach has got better of Pujara. This landed around off and spun into Pujara. Pujara comes forward and looks to defend but misses to get hit on the pad. A massive appeal and the umpire quickly raises his finger. Pujara calls for the review straightaway. But not going to work for him. He has to go as it hit the pad first. Waste of a review from him.
Flat and around off, punched to the man at covers.
Quick single. This time Rohit jumps out of the crease and flicks it towards mid on. A single taken.
Darted outside off, left alone.
Full ball on middle, flicked to square leg for one.

Big appeal for LBW but turned down. They discuss for the review but opt against it. Floated around off, Pujara comes down the track and looks to defend. Misses to get hit on the pad. A loud appeal follows but it is turned down. Leach feels that there was some bat. They get togther to discuss the DRS call and in the end opt against it.
Bouncer! This is just outside off, Rohit sits under it.
Fuller and outside off, driven towards backward point.
Back of a length and angling in from outside off. Rohit looks to punch it on the off side but it goes to mid on off the inside half of the bat.
Quick run! A leg bye. This one is on the pad, Pujara looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pad. The ball goes to square leg and they cross for a leg bye.
Back of a length ball on middle, Rohit swivels and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller and around off, kept out.

Just short of Stokes. Superb ball to end the over. An eventful first over from Leach. Loops this just around off, Pujara comes on the front foot and looks to defend. The ball takes the outside edge after spinning away a touch. The ball goes to Stokes at first slip but falls just short and Stokes takes it on the bounce. Replays show that it hit the gloves of the keeper there. This will go down as a drop then.
On middle, Rohit tucks it towards mid-wicket and gets to the other end.
Beats the bat with a beauty. Floats this one just around off, it lands and spins away to beat the forward defense of Rohit.
Floated around middle, poked towards mid on.
Short and wide outside off, Pujara slaps it to deep cover for one.

What was that? Leach fires the first one down the leg side. Pujara lets it be. Foakes moves to his left and collects. Looks like that was pre-planned delivery. Pujara likes to give the bowler charge early on but here he waited for the delivery.
Time for spin! Here's Jack Leach. A slip and a silly point in place.
Back of a length and outside off, Rohit offers no shot again.
Wide outside off, left alone.
Fuller and around off again. Played to mid on.
Good length and around off, Rohit takes a big stride forward and defends it towards backward point. Bess there runs to his left and stops the ball.
Full and outside off, pushed hard to the man at mid off.
Fullish and around off, Rohit looks to defend but it goes to mid on off the inner half.
Another sharp delivery from Stokes. It is closer to around off. Pujara watchfully leaves it alone.
In the channel outside off, Pujara makes a leave.
Pujara is having some issue with the sightscreen.
Shortish and around off, Pujara blocks.
Around off on a length, kept out.
A jaffa from Stokes! Top stuff. A sharp bouncer around off. Pujara drops his wrists and sways away from the firing line.
Stokes runs in and bowls it wide outside off now. Pujara is not interested.
And again! 5th leave in the over. Anderson need to make the batters play.
Shapes away after landing just outside off. Rohit leaves it alone.
Fuller ball around off, solidly blocked back to the bowler.
Too wide again for the batter. Rohit is not keen again.
Fuller and wider this time. Rohit makes a watchful leave.
Wide outside off, left alone by Rohit.
Good length and around off, solidly defended.
Around off on a good length. Cheteshwar blocks.
Now bowls one on the pad. Rohit nudges it on the leg side for one.

FOUR! Oh, come on, Stokes! He is Rohit Sharma. Not going to miss out on consecutive full tosses. Stokes serves a wide full toss. Rohit creams it through cover-point and it races away to the fence. First boundary of the morning.
Rohit misses out now. A juicy high full toss. Rohit drives but finds the cover fielder.
Runs for Pujara? No, off the pads. Stokes runs in and bowls this one around off, comes back in. Pujara looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pad. The ball goes to square leg and they cross.
Fullish and around off, Rohit pushes it towards mid off.
Anderson angles this one from outside off. Rohit covers his stumps and lets it be.
Another one wide outside off. Rohit is not interested is playing at that.
Little too wide outside off, left alone.
Good length ball around off, Rohit blocks off the front foot.
Around off on a good length, kept out.
Shortish and outside off, left alone.
Lovely bouncer! The effort ball from Stokes. This is just outside off, Pujara first wanted to defend but at the last moment decides against it.
Slips the fuller ball down the leg side. Pujara looks to flick but misses.
Length ball on middle, tucked through mid-wicket for one.
Around off on a length, kept out off the back foot.
Wide outside off from Stokes. Left alone.
This is just behind good length but wide outside off. Pujara lets it be.
Fuller and wider outside off, moves away further after pitching. Pujara makes a leave.
Fuller and just outside off, poked on the off side.
Wide outside off, left alone.
Rohit waits for the ball to come closer this time and tucks it towards mid on and crosses for a single.

Rohit gets hit on the pad again. Lovely stuff from Anderson so far. Once again he makes the ball to jag back in. This one pitches around off and middle and comes in to strike Rohit high on the thigh pad.
Shortish ball angled in, tucked ont the leg side. A maiden from Stokes to begin.
In the channel outside off, shapes further away. Pujara leaves it alone.
Good length and outside off, kept out off the back foot.
Full and wide, asking Pujara to go for the drive. The Indian no. 3 is not keen for offers like these, that too this early in the day.
Outside off, left alone.
A back of a length ball around off, Pujara keeps it out off the back foot.
Will it be Stokes from the other end? Yes, it is Stokes.
A mild LBW appeal but nothing from the umpire. No review from England. This one once again landed outside off and jagged back in sharply. Rohit looks to defend but got hit high on the pad again.
Full and wide outside off, Rohit goes for the drive but it takes the thick outside edge and goes towards point.
Length ball around off, pushed towards backward point.
Just outside off on a good length, this time Rohit gets right behind the line to block it.

Ohhh! Rohit got to be careful. That came in a long way after pitching way outside off. Rohit didn't account for the inward movement and he wanted to leave it alone. The ball comes back in and hits him high on the pad.
Runs straightaway for Rohit and India. A little too full ball on middle, Rohit flicks it through mid-wicket and scampers back for a couple. Positive start from him.

Right! Time for the action on Day 2. The two umpires stride out in the middle and the English players follow them in the middle. Rohit Sharma and Cheteshwar Pujara will resume the batting. James Anderson will start with the ball. Got a wicket in the first over on Day 1. Two slips and a gully in place. Here we go...

Pitch report - Deep Dasgupta is alongside Ajit Agarkar for the pitch inspection. Agarkar feels that England wouldn't be pleased with their performance with the bat. Adds that there was some turn for the spinners towards the end. Says the red ball gives a bit of extra time for the batters compared against the Pink ball. Reckons it is still a good wicket for batting. Feels the pacers can extract some reverse swing from one of the ends.

Usually, Day 3 is called the moving day of a Test but here Day 2 can be the one that decides the fate of the game. Can England strike early and push the Indians under pressure? Or will the Indians be able to put on a big first innings score to take control of the game? Big first session coming up.

Hello and welcome to the second day of the final Test between India and England. The hosts dominated day 1 with the ball and are in a strong position in this game. They will hope to bat the whole day and ensure they have a big lead. So far, the Indian batting display has been below their high standards and they'll look to correct that. England, on the other hand,  will have to find a way to keep India at bay. Their bowlers will need to be at their best if that is to happen.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

That is it from Day 1 of the final Test between India and England. The visitors are on the back foot at the end of the day but by no means out of it. Their bowlers will have to do the job with the ball and restrict India to a minimal total. India, on the other hand, will look to build on their solid showing on day 1. How will things pan out in this Test? Join us on Friday, 5th March for Day 2 of this Test. The action will begin at 0930 local (0400 GMT). Make sure you join us. Till then, goodbye and take care!

The pacer who impressed with the ball for India, Mohammed Siraj is caught for a chat. He says that the wicket is a batting wicket and he had one plan and that was to bowl at one area patiently. Goes onto say that Kohli told him that they will keep rotating the faster bowlers as they will get enough rest. States that when he was playing in Australia, he always wanted to give his full effort and that is the case even in the series. Says that they would look to bat as much as they can.

It was a day that clearly belonged to India. The bowlers once again delivered as the spinners continued the tale of the tape as they continued to spin web around England's batters, Axar and Ashwin were in the thick of action picking up 7 wickets between them. The hosts lost Gill in the very first over of their innings. It looked like it could be a tricky end to the day but Rohit and Pujara ensured there were no further damage and India finish a dominant day.

After opting to bat, England could not capitalize on it. Root would have hoped for a good start and a big total but that was not to be. Bairstow, Pope, and Lawrence all got starts but failed to convert it. Stokes' fifty was the saving grace in an otherwise timid batting display as the visitors could not bat the day out and were bundled out for 205! James Anderson started well with the ball as he got rid of Gill early. He kept things tight but there was no other success to end the day for England.

A very solid day for India and they will be the happier side at the end of Day 1 without any doubts. England will be happy that they got a wicket but will be disappointed how things panned out throughout the day.
Flatter on the pads, Pujara looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. With that, it is STUMPS ON DAY 1.
Flatter ball outside off, Pujara plays it to deep point.
Tosed up on off, Pujara taps it to the first slip fielder.
A couple now! Short and outside off, Pujara punches it to deep cover for a couple.
Flatter ball on off, Pujara defends it to silly point.
Full on the pads, Pujara uses his feet and then nudges it to mid-wicket.
Flatter ball on middle, Sharma plays it out onto the pitch.
Short ball down the leg side, Sharma leaves it alone.
Floated ball on the pads, Sharma looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads.
On off, pushed to cover for a single.
Nearly a wicket! Floated ball on off, Pujara flicks but does so uppishly. Luckily for Pujara, it lands short of the fielder at short leg.
Short ball on middle, Rohit pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Flighted ball on middle, Pujara uses his feet and then plays it to long on for a single. No Ball signalled by the third umpire.
Floated on off, Sharma pushes it to cover.
On off, defended to cover.
Tossed up on off, Sharma attempts to defend but gets an outside edge which goes past the slip fielder for a couple.
Flatter and outside off, played to deep cover for a single.
Flatter ball outside off, punched to point.
Flighted ball on middle, Pujara looks to defend but gets an inside edge which goes to the fine leg region for a couple.
That is 5 maidens in a row for James Anderson! Good length ball outside off, Sharma has no problems in leaving it alone.
Full ball on off, Sharma drives it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle, defended back to the bowler.No run.
Outside off, left alone by Rohit.
Fullish ball on off, Sharma pushes it to cover.
Good length ball on middle, Sharma defends it back to the bowler.
FOUR! That's nicely played by Pujara! Flatter ball outside off, Pujara guides it to the third man region for a boundary.
Flatter ball on off, Pujara defends it to cover.
Loopy ball on middle and leg, Pujara defends it out solidly.
Loopy ball on middle, Pujara defends it back to Leach.
Tossed up on off, played towards mid off by Pujara.
Floated on the pads, Pujara uses his feet and then flicks it through the mid-wicket region for a couple.
Back of a length ball on middle, Sharma blocks it back to the bowler.
Fullish ball on off, Sharma defends it to cover.
Back of a length ball outside off, Sharma looks to punch it off the back foot but it goes off the upper half of the bat and rolls to point.
Good length ball outside off, Sharma shoulders arms to it.
On a length on off, Rohit blocks it out onto the pitch.
Good length ball on middle, Sharma nudges it to the leg side.
Loopy ball on off, Pujara defends it off the front foot.
Flatter ball outside off, Pujara cuts it to point.
Good shot for a couple! Full on the pads, Pujara gets down to the pitch of the ball and flicks it through mid-wicket for a couple.
Outside off, punched to deep cover for a single.
Flatter ball on off, Sharma looks to defend but gets a leading edge towards cover. Pujara wants the single but is sent back by Rohit.
Leach starts with a floated ball outside off, Sharma leaves it alone.
Spin time! Jack Leach comes on in the 6th over. Just like Axar Patel came on for India in the 6th over.
Full ball outside off, left alone by Pujara.
Back of a length ball on middle, Pujara defends it out.
Fullish ball on middle, Pujara bunts it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle, Pujara defends it to mid on.
Fullish ball outside off, Pujara has no problems in letting it go to the keeper.
Back of a length ball outside off, Pujara watches it carefully and then shoulders arms to it.
Fullish ball on middle, RS is solid in defense.
Good length ball on middle, Sharma flicks it to mid-wicket.
On a length on off, Sharma blocks it solidly towards cover.
Good length ball on middle, worked to the leg side.
Good length ball on middle, Sharma defends it back to the bowler.
Fullish ball on off, Sharma prods forward and then blocks it to cover.
Back of a length ball on middle, Pujara rocks on his back foot and then defends it out.
Full ball on off, Pujara defends it off the front foot.
Good length ball outside off, Pujara shoulders arms to it.
Outside off, left alone by Cheteshwar.
Full on off, Pujara prods forward and then defends it to cover.
Good length ball on middle, Pujara defends it to the leg side.
Short ball outside off, Sharma sways away from it.
On a length on middle, Sharma flicks it to mid-wicket.
EDGED AND FOUR! Sharma is off the mark in an edgy manner! Good length ball outside off, Sharma looks to drive but it takes the outside edge and it goes past gully for a boundary.
Back of a length ball on middle, Sharma hops and then defends it out.
Stokes goes full and outside off, Sharma lets it go to the keeper.
Low full toss on off, Sharma drives it to extra cover. Missed out on a potential scoring opportunity here.
England playing just one frontline seamer in this Test so who will bowl from the other end?  Will it be Ben Stokes or a spinner? It is going to be Ben Stokes.
Excellent first over from Anderson comes to an end! A wicket-maiden! Full ball outside off, Pujara lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Pujara is solid in defense. No run.
Full ball on off, Pujara defends it to mid off.
India's new-age wall, Cheteshwar Pujara walks out to bat. He has not had a very good series according to his high standards.

OUT! LBW! Umpire's call it is and India lose a wicket in the very first over of their first innings. Gill's poor form continues in this series and he has to walk back. Perfect start for England. This is just what they needed after posting a low score. Anderson bowls a good length ball on middle and leg, Gill looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. England appeal and the finger goes up. Gill has a chat with his partner and then signals the 'T'. There is nothing on Ultra Edge while the Ball Tracker shows that it is umpire's call on hitting the stumps. Brilliant from Anderson.

Bright start for England as they have got Shubman Gill adjudged LBW. The Indian opener though has decided to take the review. Can the replays save him or will England get off to a perfect start with the ball?
Good length ball on middle, Gill defends it out solidly towards mid on.
Anderson starts with an outswinger on off, Gill drives it towards mid on.

Right then! Virat Kohli lifts the trophy and India take the series 3-1 and have booked a place to face New Zealand in the WTC final to played in June, 2021. England, on the other hand, have been outplayed and they will look to come back stronger in their next series. Tests are done now and it is time for the limited-over series. First up is the T20Is which will be played in Ahmedabad. The first one is on 12th March 2021 at 1900 local (1330 GMT). Do join us for that. Until then, cheers and take care.

Virat Kohli, the INDIAN SKIPPER, says the comeback after the loss in the first Test pleased him the most, England outplayed them in the first game, the toss became very crucial in the first Test but from the next game onwards it became more interesting and the comeback pleased him the most. States their bench strength is very strong and that is a great sign for Indian cricket, they want the youngsters to play fearless cricket and that is what they are doing, especially Axar, Pant and Sundar. Adds they are happy they are winning so many series but they need to keep learning, they can't take things lightly and always have to be at their best. Adds Ashwin has been a banker for them and his performance speaks, Rohit's knock was the defining moment of them coming back into the series and it is one of his best knocks which gave them the momentum which they needed to get back into the series. Ends by saying the WTC was more of a distraction so far for them but now they are in the finals and he is happy about it.

Ravichandran Ashwin, the MAN OF THE SERIES, says that the fact that they have qualified for the WTC final is pleasing and after they lost the first Test, the intensity was low but they have come back well. Adds that the players stood up and they have had a good series win. Tells that the last four months have been very good for him and he was not in good form with the bat but in Chennai, the moment arrived and he scored a century. Says that the kind of confidence the team management gave in him was motivating and he did not expect him to play in Australia but Kohli and  Shastri saw something in him and he says that this is the best month that he has had in his career. Tells that being content is not the greatest but being happy is very important for him and he goes back every day trying to be happy. Says that Rishabh has been amazing and he could not be more happier for him and he has been compared to legends already. Goes onto say that the way he has kept in this series is outstanding. Mentions that Axar is someone who came in Jaddu's position and he bowled extremely well and he deserves every bit of praise.

Rishabh Pant, the MAN OF THE MATCH, says he feels the hardwork he has put in is paying off and that has also given him confidence. Mentions his batting performance has given him the confidence to keep well. States his knock was important as they were in a tough situation when he came out to bat and he is happy about his performance. Adds he has always wanted to enjoy while playing and that is what is in his mind all the time.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that the first positive was the first Test but they could not match India in the rest. Adds that they will continue to learn and believes that they will become a better side from this experience. States that India managed to take home the advantage at crucial times and the partnership between Sundar and Pant was magnificent. States that India outplayed them and wishes India best of luck for the final. Goes onto say that Ahmedabad has a brilliant stadium and it has been a good experience. Says that they can look for excuses but the rotation policy is not going to go away and they cannot be playing guys until they fall over and they look at what's next as well and they want to look after their players. Mentions that it has been a very good series and they have been looked at well.

Ravi Shastri is up now for a chat. He says that when youngsters are coming through the ranks, it is pleasing to see. Adds that what Pant and Sundar did was amazing and they have worked really hard to get to the top of the table. Says that the boys just took one series at a time and they were not bothered about the WTC final. Says that they deserved to be in the final. Goes onto say that the first Test in Chennai would have been different had they got more rest but does not take the credit away from England as they outplayed them. Says that the groundsman in Ahmedabad is an amazing curator and the scoreline does not show how close this series was. Tells that he is waiting to get out of the bubble and it is time for the bubble to burst. Goes onto say that the players' first prayer is to get out of the bubble. Goes onto say that it is tough to stay in a bubble and these guys have been magnificent. Tells that the most important thing is teamwork and there is no single individual and it is 6-7 players performing at a time. States that they have been on top, they have been in trouble but they fought from there and not just in Australia but here as well. Adds the support staff have put in hours of work and it is very easy to be hard on the boys but empathy has to be shown especially in the times they live in. Goes onto say that Pant is a genuine match-winner and has worked very hard and the results are here to see. Mentions that he was fearless especially in the first innings as he played against his nature as he built his innings and that confidence rubbed off on Sundar. Adds that his keeping was superb.

Washington Sundar comes up now. He says that he is very happy to win the series and he is very happy to contribute. States that he is not disappointed on missing out on a hundred and his time will come later on. States that if the team could succeed because of his performance, that makes him happy. Says that the pitch was very good to bat on and it was doing something on Day 2 but they all felt that the wicket was good overall and it was also a challenging wicket.

Axar Patel is up for a chat. He says that he could do this after the confidence he got in the first game that he played. Adds that when he and Ashwin were bowling, his plan was to vary the speed and he bowled with the same speed in the last two Test matches. Goes onto say that when he came back to the dressing room, he did not get time to talk to Washington Sundar after India's innings but will have a chat with him now.

The visitors then bowled well and did keep themselves in the game but the Indian lower order, Pant, Sundar and Axar added more than 200 runs to put India in the driver's seat. Once a big lead was taken, it was always going to be difficult for England to get back in the game and they ended up surrendering quite easily. Stay tuned for the presentation ceremony.

England, on the other hand, should have done better not only in this innings but in this Test. They won the toss again and elected to bat but did so poorly. They should have scored a lot more than 205 on a wicket which was not that bad to bat on. However, no batter showed application and the willingness to grind it out in the middle. It was a combined effort from the Indian bowlers to restrict England to a low score in the first innings.

Once again it was the two spinners who starred for the Indians! Ashwin and Axar bowled almost all of the overs India did in this innings and bagged 5 each and it just took them a little over one session to bowl this English side out. Brilliant bowling performance from the Indian spinners and they have hammered England in this series.

An emphatic win for for the Indians! England have just surrendered! Very poor display of batting once again from their side as they have let India inflict an innings defeat. With this win, India not only win the series 3-1 but also ensure their place in the finals of the WTC against New Zealand.

Full on middle, Sibley gets to the pitch of the ball and then flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Quicker on off, Dom taps it to first slip.
Shortish and around off, Sibley looks to flick but gets hit on the pads.
Flatter ball on off, Sibley plays it back to the bowler.
Flatter ball outside off, Root plays it to cover for a single.
Flighted on the pads, Root defends it back to the bowler.
Top edge but safe! Flighted ball on middle, Root looks to sweep but it takes the top edge and goes towards deep square leg where it falls short of the fielder. A couple taken.
Flatter ball outside off, Root punches it to cover-point.
Quicker ball on middle, Root goes back in his crease and then blocks it out onto the pitch.
Flighted ball on off, Root prods forward and then defends it to the cover region.
Shortish on the pads, Root pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
On the pads, tucked to the leg side.
Flatter on middle, Root defends it back to the bowler.
Floated on off, Sibley uses his feet and then pushes it to long on for a single.
Tossed up on off, Root goes on his knees and then sweeps it to backward square leg for a single.
Flighted ball on middle, Root nudges it down to mid on for nothing.
Loopy ball on off, pushed wide of mid off for a single.
Full on middle, Root pushes it back to the bowler.
Outside off, left alone.

An appeal for LBW turned down! Flighted ball on the pads, Root looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but the umpire says no. Kohli, Pant and Axar are involved in a discussion about whether to take the review but decide not to. The Ball Tracker rolls in and it shows that it was umpire's call on hitting the stumps.
Flighted ball outside off, it spun away. Root watches it carefully and leaves it alone.
Flighted ball on middle, Root defends it back to the bowler.
No Hat-Trick for Ashwin! Root plays this full ball on middle to square leg for a single. A brilliant start from Ashwin.
Joe Root is the next man in.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SHORT LEG! Bairstow goes for a first-ball duck and England lose two-in-two. Excellent captaincy from Virat Kohli. Kept a fielder there for this shot and it has worked to perfection. End of a tough series for Jonny Bairstow. This is the third duck for him in 4 innings. Flighted ball on middle, Bairstow flicks but it goes uppishly towards short leg where Rohit Sharma takes a good catch. Ashwin is on a Hat-Trick now. What a start for India!
Jonny Bairstow comes out to bat at number 3.

OUT! CAUGHT AT FIRST SLIP! Ashwin strikes in his first over and this is the perfect start for India in the second session. Crawley's Test is over and he does not create much of an impact. Ashwin tosses this one up around off, Crawley prods forward to defend but it takes the outside edge and it goes to first slip where Rahane pouches it safely. England still trail by 150 runs and have 9 wickets in hand.
On off, pushed to cover.

FOUR LEG BYES! Vicious turn! Nothing much Rishabh Pant could have done there! Flighted ball on middle, it spins a lot. Crawley looks to flick but it brushes his pads and goes to the fine leg region for four leg byes.
Ashwin starts with a floated ball on off, Crawley defends it out to the off side.
Ravichandran Ashwin will bowl from the other end.
Floated ball outside off, Sibley lets it go to the keeper.
Full on middle, Sibley pushes it back to Axar.
Floated ball on middle and leg, Sibley blocks it out onto the bat.
Loopy ball on off, Sibley strides forward and solidly blocks it to cover.
Flighted ball on middle, Dom defends it back to the bowler.
Axar starts with a full ball on off, Sibley prods forward and then plays it back to the bowler.
We are back for the start of the second session of Day 3. The Indian players stride out to the middle, followed by Dom Sibley and Zak Crawley. Axar Patel will start with the ball.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

So first mission achieved for England. They have gone through the nervy period unscathed after India got a lead of 160, courtesy a fine batting performance from Washington Sundar, Axar Patel and Rishabh Pant who scored a century on Day 2. There’s still a long way to go though in the test. The visitors will need a good opening stand. India, on the other hand, just have to be patient and hope their bowlers can do what they have been doing throughout this series. Stay tuned for the afternoon session which will begin at 1210 local (0640 GMT).

Excellent stop by Siraj! Full ball on off, Crawley drives it crisply towards the bowler. Siraj, on his followthrough dives and does really well to stop. He seemed to have hurt himself in the process and is in some pain. He gets up and walks back along with the physio. LUNCH ON DAY 3.
On a length on middle, Crawley flicks it through the square leg region for a couple of runs.

Good fielding from Washington Sundar! Full ball on the pads, Sibley flicks it to the backward square leg region. Sundar comes across from fine leg, slides and makes a good stop. Keeps it down to a single.
On a length on middle, Dom works it to mid-wicket.
Good length ball on off, Sibley prods forward and then blocks it to cover.
Full delivery on middle, Zak flicks it wide of mid on for a single.
Floated ball on middle, Sibley looks to defend but gets an inside edge which goes to the leg side. No harm done.
Full on middle, Sibley uses his feet and then looks to flick but gets a leading edge which goes towards cover.
Probably going down leg! Flatter ball on the pads, Sibley looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. There is a mild appeal for LBW but the umpire says no.
Flatter ball on the pads, Zak flicks it to the square leg region for a single.
BEATEN! Lovely ball from Axar! He tosses this one outside off, Crawley looks to defend but the ball spins away a little and beats the outside edge of Crawley's bat.
Patel starts with a flighted ball on off, Crawley drives it to mid off.
Who will bowl from the other end? Axar Patel it is.
Crawley and England are underway! Good length ball on the pads, Crawley flicks it to deep square leg for a single.
Good length ball outside the off stump line, Crawley shoulders arms to it.
Siraj gets this one to come back in. He bowls a length ball on middle, Crawley though is up for the challenge as he flicks it to square leg.
On a length outside the off stump line, Crawley shoulders arms to it.
We are all set to begin England's second innings! The Indian players make their way out to the middle, followed by Zak Crawley and Dom Sibley. Mohammed Siraj will start with the ball.
Full ball outside off, Crawley has once again no problems in leaving it alone.
Siraj starts with a good length ball outside off, Crawley lets it through to the keeper.
